<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10029d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10029d">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10029d"> 29(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> demotic / hieratic / hieroglyphic</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">On distingue chez les Egyptiens trois esp&egrave;ces d&apos;&eacute;critures diff&eacute;rentes: La premi&egrave;re compos&eacute;e de caract&egrave;res semblables &agrave; ceux employ&eacute;s dans l&apos;&eacute;criture cursive et connue sous le nom de <i>populaire</i> ou <mark><i>d&eacute;motique</i></mark> (fig 1); La seconde, dont les caract&egrave;res ressemblent un peu &agrave; ceux de la premi&egrave;re et qu&apos;on appelle <mark><i>hi&eacute;ratique</i></mark> ou <i>sacerdotale</i> (fig 2); Enfin la troisi&egrave;me appel&eacute;e <mark><i>hi&eacute;roglyphique</i></mark> et qui est compos&eacute;e de caract&egrave;res repr&eacute;sentant des objects naturels ou artificiels (fig. 3); c&apos;&eacute;tait l&apos;&eacute;criture symbolique des anciens &Eacute;gyptiens. <font color="green">[We can distinguish among the Egyptians three types of different writing. The first consists of characters similar to the ones used in cursive writing and is known as popular or demotic writing (fig. 1). The second has characters that are a little similar to the first and is called hieratic or sacerdotal (fig. 2). Finally, the third is called hieroglyphic and consists of characters that represent natural or artificial objects (fig. 3); this was the symbolic writing of the Ancient Egyptians.]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 13-4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
